## 35. AI Limitations & Risk Disclosure

The following limitations must be prominently disclosed in the application wherever AI recommendations are presented, and summarized in the "Coming Soon" ML preview section:

| # | Limitation | Description |
|---|-----------|-------------|
| 1 | **Cannot predict the future** | AI learns from historical data assuming past behavior repeats. Sudden events break patterns instantly. |
| 2 | **Lacks contextual understanding** | Detects patterns but cannot interpret real-world significance or market overreaction. |
| 3 | **False signals are common** | Even top systems achieve only 50-60% directional accuracy. False positives and negatives are frequent. |
| 4 | **Overfitting risk** | Models may perform well in backtests but fail in live markets. |
| 5 | **Black swan vulnerability** | Least reliable during crises, geopolitical shocks, and collapses — when guidance matters most. |
| 6 | **Data quality dependency** | Delayed/inaccurate data, misinterpreted sentiment, and manipulated social media produce unreliable signals. |
| 7 | **No intuition or judgment** | Cannot replicate experience-based gut instinct or deep understanding of human psychology. |
| 8 | **Crowding effect** | As more traders adopt similar AI models, signals lose effectiveness. |
| 9 | **Timing difficulty** | Even when directionally correct, signals may be too early or too late. |
| 10 | **Not truly autonomous** | AI serves as decision support. Humans remain responsible for interpreting signals and making final decisions. |

